Also some nice facts to know:

  • A prime p>2p>2p>2p>2 cannot end with a 0,2,4,50,2,4,50,2,4,50,2,4,5 or 8888.
  • A number is divisible by 3333 if the sum of the digits are divisible by 3333.

The number of zeroes at the end of a number can be determined by the number of factors of 2222 and 5555 since 10=5\cdot210=5⋅210=5\cdot210=5⋅2. How many pairs of 2222 and 5555 can we make? For example, let us consider 10!10!10!10!:

10! = 10\cdot9\cdot8\cdot7\cdot6\cdot5\cdot4\cdot3\cdot2\cdot1 = (5\cdot2)\cdot9\cdot2^3\cdot7\cdot(3\cdot2)\cdot5\cdot2^2\cdot3\cdot2

So we have two 5555's and eight 2222's which means we can make two pairs of 5555 and 2222. Therefore, the number ends with two zeros. It's easy to verify using a calculator 10! =362880010!=362880010! =362880010!=3628800.

Definition: Two numbers nnnn and mmmm are relatively prime if \gcd(n,m)=1gcd⁡(n,m)=1\gcd(n,m)=1gcd(n,m)=1. (They have no common factors other than 1111)

Definition: \phi(n)ϕ(n)\phi(n)ϕ(n) is the number of integers in \{1,2,3,\ldots,n-1, n\}{1,2,3,…,n−1,n}\{1,2,3,\ldots,n-1, n\}{1,2,3,…,n−1,n} which are relatively prime to nnnn.

There are p^kpkp^kpk numbers 1,2,3,4,\ldots, p^k-1, p^k1,2,3,4,…,pk−1,pk1,2,3,4,\ldots, p^k-1, p^k1,2,3,4,…,pk−1,pk between 1111 and p^kpkp^kpk. We want to find out how many of these are relatively prime to p^kpkp^kpk. Let us instead count how many of these are not relatively prime to p^kpkp^kpk:

For mmmm to have a common factor with p^kpkp^kpk (other than 1111), it has to be divisible by pppp, so the only numbers not relatively prime to p^kpkp^kpk are p, 2p, 3p, \ldots, (p-1)p, p^2, 2p^2 \ldots, (p-1)p^2, p^3, 2p^3,\ldots, (p-1)p^{k-1}, p^kp,2p,3p,…,(p−1)p,p2,2p2…,(p−1)p2,p3,2p3,…,(p−1)pk−1,pkp, 2p, 3p, \ldots, (p-1)p, p^2, 2p^2 \ldots, (p-1)p^2, p^3, 2p^3,\ldots, (p-1)p^{k-1}, p^kp,2p,3p,…,(p−1)p,p2,2p2…,(p−1)p2,p3,2p3,…,(p−1)pk−1,pk. That is, there are p^{k-1}pk−1p^{k-1}pk−1 out of p^kpkp^kpk numbers not relatively prime to p^kpkp^kpk so we have \phi(p^k)=p^k-p{k-1}=p^{k-1}(p-1)ϕ(pk)=pk−pk−1=pk−1(p−1)\phi(p^k)=p^k-p{k-1}=p^{k-1}(p-1)ϕ(pk)=pk−pk−1=pk−1(p−1).

History: Here is the original theorem from Leonhard Euler's paper, "Theoremata arithmetica nova methodo demonstrate" ("Demonstration of a new method in the theory of arithmetic"), published 1763. (Source)

If you don't like the solution -2−2-2−2 we can make it to be a number between 1111 and 9999 as follows: -2\equiv -2 + 9 \equiv 7 \pmod 9−2≡−2+9≡7(mod9)-2\equiv -2 + 9 \equiv 7 \pmod 9−2≡−2+9≡7(mod9) so an inverse of 4444 modulo 9999 is 7777.

Suppose both xxxx and yyyy are solutions to the system of congruences. In other words:

are true. By the previous exercise, we can conclude that x\equiv y\pmod mx≡y(modm)x\equiv y\pmod mx≡y(modm) where m=m_1m_2\cdots m_nm=m1m2⋯mnm=m_1m_2\cdots m_nm=m1​m2​⋯mn​.

By using the CRT:

  • M_2 = \frac{2\cdot 3}{3}=2M2=2⋅33=2M_2 = \frac{2\cdot 3}{3}=2M2​=32⋅3​=2

Now we want to find an inverse y_kyky_kyk​ of M_kMkM_kMk​ modulo m_kmkm_kmk​ for k=1,2k=1,2k=1,2k=1,2. In other words, we want to solve M_k y_k\equiv 1\pmod{m_k}Mkyk≡1(modmk)M_k y_k\equiv 1\pmod{m_k}Mk​yk​≡1(modmk​) for y_kyky_kyk​ for k=1,2k=1,2k=1,2k=1,2:

  • 3y_1\equiv1\pmod 2\implies3y1≡1(mod2)  ⟹  3y_1\equiv1\pmod 2\implies3y1​≡1(mod2)⟹ we can choose y_1=1y1=1y_1=1y1​=1 since 3\cdot1=3\equiv1\pmod23⋅1=3≡1(mod2)3\cdot1=3\equiv1\pmod23⋅1=3≡1(mod2).
  • 2y_2\equiv1\pmod3\implies2y2≡1(mod3)  ⟹  2y_2\equiv1\pmod3\implies2y2​≡1(mod3)⟹ we can coose y_2=2y2=2y_2=2y2​=2 because 2\cdot2=4\equiv1\pmod32⋅2=4≡1(mod3)2\cdot2=4\equiv1\pmod32⋅2=4≡1(mod3).

Now, we can construct a solution as in the proof of the CRT:

M=a_1M_1y_1 + a_2M_2y_2 = 1\cdot3\cdot1+1\cdot2\cdot2 = 7M=a1M1y1+a2M2y2=1⋅3⋅1+1⋅2⋅2=7M=a_1M_1y_1 + a_2M_2y_2 = 1\cdot3\cdot1+1\cdot2\cdot2 = 7M=a1​M1​y1​+a2​M2​y2​=1⋅3⋅1+1⋅2⋅2=7

This is only one possible solution! To find all solutions, we can add/subtract multiples of m_1\cdot m_2 = 6m1⋅m2=6m_1\cdot m_2 = 6m1​⋅m2​=6 so the general solutions are integers on the form x=7+6kx=7+6kx=7+6kx=7+6k for an integer kkkk.

Direct approach:
We want x=2k+1x=2k+1x=2k+1x=2k+1 and x=3l+1x=3l+1x=3l+1x=3l+1 for some integers kkkk and llll. So we are interested in the case 2k=3l\iff k=\frac{3}{2}l2k=3l  ⟺  k=32l2k=3l\iff k=\frac{3}{2}l2k=3l⟺k=23​l. But for kkkk to be an integer, we need that llll is even so l=2ml=2ml=2ml=2m for some mmmm. Consequently, we have that k=6mk=6mk=6mk=6m for some integer mmmm and therefore x=6m+1x=6m+1x=6m+1x=6m+1.

Question: Can you see that both approaches give the same solutions?
